model.name: AI Maturity Assessment
model.description: Evaluate your organization's AI readiness and maturity across key dimensions including strategy, infrastructure, talent, and implementation capabilities.

maturityScale.name: Explore
maturityScale.description: Organizations experiment with isolated AI pilots led by enthusiasts, but lack strategic direction, governance, and coordinated leadership, resulting in limited business impact and “pilot paralysis.”

maturityScale.name: Build
maturityScale.description: Companies begin laying strategic and technical foundations for AI, investing in data infrastructure and governance, with formal leadership emerging but business value still constrained by talent gaps and low adoption.

maturityScale.name: Scale
maturityScale.description: AI is deployed across multiple business functions with measurable impact, supported by cross-functional governance and strong business-technology alignment, though scaling is challenged by workforce retraining and cultural resistance.

maturityScale.name: Transform
maturityScale.description: AI becomes a strategic driver embedded in core operations and decision-making, championed by C-suite leaders, delivering competitive advantages through innovation, personalization, and operational efficiency.

maturityScale.name: Frontier
maturityScale.description: The organization reinvents its business model with an AI-first culture, treating AI as an omnipresent utility, enabling dynamic human–AI teams and autonomous systems that continuously optimize operations and set new industry standards

dimensions.label: Strategy & Leadership
dimensions.description: The organization’s vision, executive sponsorship, and strategic alignment ensure AI initiatives are prioritized, funded, and integrated with high-value business goals.

dimensions.label: Talent & Skills
dimensions.description: The workforce is equipped with the necessary AI expertise, upskilling programs, and cross-functional collaboration to drive adoption and innovation.

dimensions.label: Data & Infrastructure
dimensions.description: Robust data pipelines, cloud platforms, and secure infrastructure provide the technical foundation for scalable, reliable, and high-impact AI solutions.

dimensions.label: Use Case Integration
dimensions.description: AI is embedded into core business processes and products, with measurable outcomes tied to enterprise KPIs and operational workflows.

dimensions.label: Governance & Responsible AI
dimensions.description: Ethical, secure, and transparent AI practices are institutionalized through strong governance frameworks, risk management, and compliance with emerging regulations.

dimensions.label: Culture & Change Management
dimensions.description: An AI-ready culture fosters agility, experimentation, and continuous learning, supported by effective change management and broad workforce engagement.

questions.text: How mature is your organization’s use of agentic AI (from platform-provided agents to fully coded, tool-using agents)?

answers.text: No agentic AI in use; experimentation blocked or limited to generic chat; no policies or evaluation criteria.
Platform-provided agents only (e.g., built-in Copilot features like meeting recap, draft/Researcher); ad hoc, not integrated with business systems.
Simple declarative or site/department agents (e.g., SharePoint/Teams scoped helpers) with limited actions; basic governance and telemetry.
Low‑code custom agents built with Copilot Studio (tools/actions, approvals, connectors to LoB systems); pilots in multiple functions; usage measured.
Production‑grade coded agents using Azure AI Foundry/Functions with tool‑use, retrieval, function calling, and CI/CD; cataloged, monitored, and continuously evaluated.

questions.text: How mature is your organizational access and licensing approach for AI tools and agents?

answers.text: No official access; AI tools blocked or unmanaged; employees either abstain or experiment off the record.
Ad hoc personal use of free/consumer tools (e.g., ChatGPT, Gemini); no SSO, no data controls; shadow usage prevalent.
Selective licensing for paid premium tools (e.g., Microsoft 365 Copilot, ChatGPT Enterprise, Gemini for select roles); basic governance and monitoring. Some agent use.
Mixed model: broader access to official free tools and pay‑as‑you‑go agents, plus selective premium seats; SSO, audit, DLP, and cost controls in place.  Agentic AI is common.
Enterprise‑wide enablement: full licensing for most/all workforce where appropriate; multi‑vendor options brokered; role‑based provisioning, RBAC, SSO, audit, and charge‑back.
